Hey Cousins!!! Here’s the key to making super moist Southern style dressing this #thanksgiving! 

1. Heat a heavy bottom skillet with a little oil to medium high. Spray 9x13 casserole dish with non stick spray and set aside. Pre heat oven to 375. 2. Dice 1 sweet onion, 1 green bell pepper, and 1 stalk of celery. Cook 1 cup of chicken gizzards or Turkey giblets....with 1 cup of country sausage (chicken, pork or Turkey) and diced veggies.  3. Once cooked all the way through (about 3 to 4 mins) remove from heat and cool. 4. Add cooled meat and veggie mixture to a food processor. Pulse until meat and veggies are really fine but not mushy. 5. In a large bowl add meat mixture, 1 and a half bags of plain yellow cornbread stuffing. You can also use day old cornbread made from scratch (you’ll need about 3 cups). Add cornbread to bowl. Add 1 1/2 cups of chicken stock, 1 cup of whole milk, and  1 1/2 sticks of melted unsalted butter. Now add seasoning....about  2 teaspoons of salt, pepper , garlic powder, dried Italian seasoning and rubbed sage or fresh sage (I used about 2 tablespoons of fresh sage.....always use less when using dried herbs). Give it a mix and then add in 2 whole eggs. Spread into casserole dish, smooth it out. Put it in the oven uncovered for 35 to 40 mins. Serve warm! node.text: Being on the road can take a toll on you. Especially when you’re staying in a hotel without a kitchen for weeks at a time. Let me tell you something….I absolutely refuse to eat out every night while filming in Tennessee. I’m doing good on my health journey and I can’t let being out of town mess that up. Because my Momma taught me better than that….I went to @walmart picked up an electric skillet, a crockpot, and some cheap cooking utensils. I have a mini fridge so I grabbed a little groceries and made a meal in my hotel room!!! Plus I saw @carlaphall and @fullerfarmer do it 😄. I meal prepped my breakfast and I made beef 🥩 & broccoli 🥦 for dinner last night….with #keto friendly noodles @miraclenoodle! It was delicious!!!! #deliciousmissbrown #ontheroad #gottamakeitdowhatitdo 😂

node.text: #Repost• @foodnetworkmag When Kardea Brown was growing up on Wadmalaw Island outside Charleston, SC, she’d often gather with family beneath the Spanish moss–covered tree in her great-grandfather’s yard, and they would spill endless buckets of boiled crab, shrimp, sausage, corn and potatoes onto a newspaper-lined table. Like crawfish boils in Louisiana and clambakes in New England, Low Country boils are a regional summer staple—they’re super fun. These days Kardea carries on the tradition with her girlfriends, hosting a boil right on the beach whenever they visit. It’s the best kind of communal eating, she says. “Instead of breaking bread, we’re breaking crab.” Swipe for her recipe! #foodnetwork #foodnetworkmagazine

node.text:
Miss Browns Beans 

1 lb ground beef (you can also use hot dogs, sausage or make it meatless) 
1 small onion diced 
1 green bell pepper diced 
3 15.8 oz Pinto Beans (slightly drained) 
1 cup your favorite BBQ Sauce (I’d suggest a sweet flavored bbq sauce…preferably with molasses) 
2 tablespoons water 
1 tablespoon yellow mustard
2 teaspoons garlic powder 
2 teaspoons sweet paprika
Salt and pepper to taste 

Directions 
Preheat oven to 300 degrees 
In a large heavy bottom skillet. Turn pan on med-hi heat, add a little neutral oil (like canola or vegetable), sauté veggies until onions become slightly translucent. Add meat, season with a few pinches of salt, pepper, garlic powder and paprika. cook ground beef (or meat of your choice) until it starts to brown. Remove from heat. In a large Dutch oven or pot, add beans, then ground meat mixture. Stir then add bbq sauce, mustard and water. Stir again and taste. Add salt and pepper to your liking. If you like your beans more soupy add a little more water and bbq sauce. Stir one last time, cover and put it in the oven. Let bake slow for 2 hours, stirring occasionally. Serve with white rice. #deliciousmissbrown #recipe #foodnetwork
